field.textValue:
To enhance data security, various measures have been adopted at the system, data, and process levels, including:

- Use of strong passwords;
- Firewalls for servers;
- Redundant and periodic backups;
- Encrypted communication channels (HTTPS/SSL);
- Periodic maintenance of servers and software, including updates to recommended versions;
- Presence of an audit trail to identify any data entry and modifications in the system;
- Requirement to provide a reason for any changes to data stored in REDCap;
- Non-linkage of participant IDs with personal data when data needs to be provided to blinded parts of the study (e.g., sponsor);
- Blocking the export of personal identification data;
- Unidentified data export allowed only for certain types of users, where applicable.

Computational Infrastructure

Cloud computing resources are used for hosting the Information and Communication Technology (ICT) systems used in the project, hosted on the private cloud of the University of São Paulo (interNuvem - https://internuvem.usp.br/). By default, interNuvem provides high availability and redundancy of access to services. Allocated resources are isolated in private networks and protected by various security mechanisms. Access to systems and servers is conducted through HTTPS and SSL connections, using digital certificates and key pairs. 

To host different software modules, pre-paid credits have been used to acquire the following computational services:
- 3 virtual web servers with Ubuntu 18.04 LTS operating system, 2 vCPU, and 4GB RAM (primary REDCap, secondary REDCap, complementary modules/software);
- MySQL Database Server, version 5.7.

Credits are consumed monthly, and their depletion may affect the availability of contracted resources. It is the responsibility of the Information and IT Management Team to monitor usage and suggest acquiring new credits to avoid potential service interruptions.

Privacy and Data Recovery

The Information and IT Management Team is responsible for safeguarding the data collected and generated throughout the study. Raw and processed data are stored in relational database servers dedicated to the project and hosted on a cloud computing platform with redundancy and high availability. REDCap and other software used in the project function as interfaces for querying and managing datasets.

The geographic location of the data, i.e., where a particular server is allocated, may vary due to the intrinsic characteristics of cloud computing platforms, which can move servers between data centers in different locations to ensure availability and low latency access to data. When possible and financially viable, preference should be given to data centers located within the national territory.

Backup copies of datasets are generated daily, with a retention period of 7 days, stored in separate locations from the original server. Backups are performed at both the server and data levels to provide multiple recovery options if needed. 

To facilitate quick disaster recovery, it is possible to restore a backup quickly on a new server, thanks to the advantages of cloud computing. Additionally, along with the main REDCap server, a reserve server with the same characteristics is kept operational, which also allows for rapid switching from primary to secondary in case of unavailability.

Finally, cloud technologies ensure much greater scalability compared to traditional approaches. During peak access times or server overloads, auxiliary resources can be quickly instantiated to keep services running.

To enhance security and privacy, various security measures are adopted at the system, data, metadata, and process levels, such as: firewalls for servers; redundant and periodic backups; encrypted communication channels (HTTPS/SSL); periodic maintenance of servers and software, including updates to recommended versions; presence of an audit trail to identify any data entry and modifications in the system; requirement to provide a reason for any changes to data stored in REDCap; non-linkage of participant IDs with personal data when data needs to be provided to blinded parts of the study (e.g., sponsor); blocking the export of personal identification data; unidentified data export allowed only for certain types of users, where applicable.

Furthermore, different access hierarchies are provided according to the type of access and privileges granted over the dataset. In the web system, each user holds an access credential. An administrator defines permissions for each user. These permissions reflect each action that an individual can or cannot perform within the system, such as the types of data viewed and available functionalities. Additionally, the system also allows the definition of different datasets, accessible in distinct contexts, which can be particularly useful for multicentric projects.

Thus, only the Information and IT Management Team provides participants with access to REDCap. At the project level, access control is fully configurable. Different access levels have been defined for Regular Users and Researchers. Each user has access only to their center's data, and simultaneous entry is allowed, except for the same form. This is necessary to ensure data integrity in REDCap.
